[{"id":"FT554756","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"Why were works like the one on the right far more popular with the nineteenth-century public and with critics than those painted by artists of the movement represented on the left?&nbsp;","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<p>LEFT:</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"A painting shows boats sailing in the water, with outlines of ships and harbor in the background. A red Sun is in the horizon.\n\" height=\"306\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/8abfd40edd797931da06f32fb52850cb/original.jpg\" width=\"400\" /></p>\n\n<p>RIGHT:</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"A painting shows a shepherd kneeling next to a girl sitting under a tree and wrapping his left arm around her shoulders. He holds an insect in his left hand close to her face. His sheep are neglected in the field in the background. The girl has a lamb and apples in her lap.\n\" height=\"228\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/6414518b4407ba11a3a04a94fcd6f4eb/original.jpg\" width=\"330\" /></p>\n"}]}]